olive oil
1 tomato
1 packet spaghetti
1 cucumber
3 clove garlic
1 packet diced bacon
20 g butter
½ bottle cream
1 sachet Chicken-Style Stock Powder
1 packet basil pesto
1 tsp balsamic vinegar
1 bag salad leaves
1 packet Grated Parmesan Cheese

Bring a large saucepan of salted water to the boil.
Roughly chop the tomato and cucumber. Finely
chop the garlic.

Cook the spaghetti in the boiling water until
'al dente', 10 minutes. Reserve some pasta water
(1/4 cup for 2 people / 1/2 cup for 4 people), then
drain and return the spaghetti to the saucepan.
Drizzle with a little olive oil to prevent sticking and
cover to keep warm.

TIP: 'Al dente' pasta is cooked through but still
slightly firm in the centre.

In a large frying pan, heat a drizzle of olive oil
over a medium-high heat. Cook the diced bacon,
breaking it up with a spoon, until golden,
4-5 minutes. Add the garlic and butter and cook
until fragrant, 1-2 minutes. Add the longlife cream
(see ingredients), chicken-style stock powder and
reserved pasta water. Season with pepper and
cook until slightly reduced, 2-3 minutes.

Remove the pan from the heat, then stir through
the basil pesto and cooked spaghetti. Season to
taste and set aside.

In a large bowl, combine the balsamic vinegar and
a drizzle of olive oil. Season, then add the mixed
salad leaves, tomato and cucumber. Toss to coat.

Divide the creamy bacon and basil pesto spaghetti
between bowls. Sprinkle with the grated
Parmesan cheese and serve with the
tomato salad.